loof, Sr.]]<ref name=\"pattersonreign\" /> || May 1979 \u2013 November 1980\n|-\n| [[Maloof family|Gavin Maloof]]<ref name=\"pattersonreign\" /> || November 1980 \u2013 June 1982\n|-\n| Charlie Thomas<ref name=\"alexanderpurchase\" /> || June 1982 \u2013 July 1993\n|-\n| [[Leslie Alexander (businessman)|Leslie Alexander]]<ref name=\"alexanderpurchase\" /> || July 1993 \u2013 October 2017\n|-\n| [[Tilman Fertitta]]<ref>{{cite web|date=October 6, 2017|url=http://www.chron.com/sports/rockets/article/It-s-official-Tilman-Fertitta-owns-the-Rockets-12259275.php?ipid=happening|title=It's official: Tilman Fertitta owns the Rockets|work=chron.com|access-date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> || October 2017 \u2013 present\n|}\n{{Columns-end}}\n\n===Coaches===\n{{Main|List of Houston Rockets head coaches}}\n;San Diego Rockets<ref name=\"cbs_houston\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"border:2px solid #FFBE00; background-color:#006633; color:#FFFFFF;\"|Coach\n! style=\"border:2px solid #FFBE00; background-color:#006633; color:#FFFFFF;\"|Tenure \n|-\n| [[Jack McMahon]] || 1968\u20131970\n|-\n| [[Alex Hannum]] || 1970\u20131971\n|}\n\n;Houston Rockets<ref name=\"cbs_houston\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Houston Rockets|border=2}};\"|Coach\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Houston Rockets|border=2}};\"|Tenure\n|-\n| [[Tex Winter]] || 1971\u20131973\n|-\n| [[Johnny Egan]] || 1973\u20131976\n|-\n| [[Tom Nissalke]] || 1976\u20131979\n|-\n| [[Del Harris]] || 1979\u20131983\n|-\n| [[Bill Fitch]] || 1983\u20131988\n|-\n| [[Don Chaney]] || 1988\u20131992\n|-\n| [[Rudy Tomjanovich]] || 1992\u20132003\n|-\n| [[Jeff Van Gundy]] || 2003\u20132007\n|-\n| [[Rick Adelman]] || 2007\u20132011\n|-\n| [[Kevin McHale (basketball)|Kevin McHale]] || 2011\u20132015\n|-\n| [[J. B. Bickerstaff]] <small>(interim)</small> || 2015\u20132016\n|-\n| [[Mike D'Antoni]] || 2016\u2013present\n|}\n\n==Politics==\nOn October 4, 2019, the Rockets' general manager [[Daryl Morey]] issued a tweet that supported [[2019 Hong Kong protests|the 2019 Hong Kong protests]], which drew criticism from the Rockets' owner [[Tilman Fertitta]] who said that while Morey was the best general manager in the NBA, the Rockets were not a political organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/rockets-gm-daryl-morey-tweets-support-for-hong-kong-protests-prompting-response-from-owner-130019981.html|title=Rockets GM Daryl Morey tweets support for Hong Kong protests, prompting response from owner|website=sports.yahoo.com|date=October 5, 2019}}</ref> Morey later deleted the tweet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rockets GM Daryl Morey in hot water after Hong Kong tweet |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nba/rockets-gm-daryl-morey-in-hot-water-after-hong-kong-tweet/ar-AAIjIMT?li=BBnba9I |agency=MSN |publisher=USA Today |date=October 5, 2019}}</ref> Morey's tweet resulted in the [[Chinese Basketball Association]]'s suspension of its relationship with the Rockets and the issuance of a statement of dissatisfaction from the consulate office of [[China]] in Houston.<ref name=apnewsrocket>{{cite news |title=Rockets' general manager's Hong Kong comments anger China |url=https://www.apnews.com/0a660e9e10664e31bf6ee359c22058cf |agency=AP |publisher=AP |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> On October 6, Morey and the NBA each issued a separate statement addressing the original tweet; Morey said that he never intended his tweet to cause any offense, while the NBA said the tweet was \"Regrettable\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Chang|first=Joy|date=October 7, 2019|title=Houston Rockets GM's Hong Kong tweet outrages Chinese fans|url=https://www.scmp.com/video/hong-kong/3031915/houston-rockets-gms-hong-kong-tweet-outrages-chinese-fans|work=SCMP|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Victor|first=Daniel|date=October 7, 2019|title=Hong Kong Protests Put N.B.A. on Edge in China|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/07/sports/basketball/nba-china-hong-kong.html|work=NYT}}</ref> The statements drew attention and subsequent bipartisan criticism from several US politicians.<ref name=apnewsrocket/> Chinese media outlets, including the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]]-run ''[[People's Daily]]'', described Morey and the NBA's statements as non-apologetic and unacceptable, because they did not contain the word \"apologize\".<ref>{{cite news |title=\u83ab\u96f7\u3001NBA\u58f0\u660e\u5747\u672a\u9053\u6b49 \u7f51\u53cb\uff1a\u8fd9\u662f\u5bf9\u4e2d\u56fd\u7684\u65e0\u89c6\u548c\u6311\u8845 |trans-title=Morey and NBA statements did not apologize. Netizen: This is a disregard and provocation against China |url=http://society.people.com.cn/n1/2019/1007/c428181-31385995.html |accessdate=October 7, 2019 |work=society.people.com.cn |publisher=[[People's Daily]] |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=NBA\u5b98\u65b9\u5f3a\u8c03\u83ab\u96f7\u4ec5\u4ee3\u8868\u4e2a\u4eba \u5168\u6587\u65e0\u60e9\u7f5a\u65e0\u9053\u6b49 |trans-title=NBA officially stressed that Morey only represents himself, no punishment, no apology issued |url=https://sports.sina.com.cn/basketball/nba/2019-10-07/doc-iicezzrr0516313.shtml |accessdate=October 7, 2019 |publisher=[[Sina Corp|Sina]] Sport |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Houston Rockets}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Houston Rockets}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle={{NBA color cell|Houston Rockets|border=2}}|list=\n{{Houston Rockets seasons}}\n{{NBArelocated}}\n{{NBA}}\n{{Texas sports}}\n{{Houston}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Houston Rockets| ]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1971 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Relocated National Basketball Association teams]]\n", "name_user": "Cowsareawsomw", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Houston_Rockets"}
{"title_page": "Lund Cathedral", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Lund Cathedral\n| fullname               = \n| image                  = Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17.jpg\n| imagesize              = \n| imagelink              = \n| imagealt               = \n| caption                = View of Lund Cathedral from the south east\n| coordinates            = {{coord|55|42|15|N|13|11|36|E|region:SE_type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| osgraw                 = \n| osgridref              = \n| location               = [[Lund]]\n| country                = [[Sweden]]\n\n| denomination           = [[Church of Sweden]]\n| previous denomination  = [[Church of Denmark]] (until 1658)<br>[[Catholic Church]] (until the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]])\n| churchmanship          = \n| membership             = \n| attendance             = \n| website                = [http://www.lundsdomkyrka.se/ Website of the Cathedral]\n\n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| founded date           = Late 11th century\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = \n| dedicated date         = \n| consecrated date       = 1123 (crypt)<br>1145 (main altar)\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = \n| past bishop            = \n| people                 = \n\n| status                 = Active\n| functional status      = Cathedral\n| heritage designation   = [[Listed buildings in Sweden|Ecclesiastical monument]] in the buildings database of the [[Swedish National Heritage Board]].<ref name=raa>{{cite web |url= http://www.bebyggelseregistret.raa.se/bbr2/anlaggning/visaHistorik.raa?anlaggningId=21300000022524&page=historik&visaHistorik=true|title= Lund kn, DOMKYRKAN 1 LUNDS DOMKYRKA|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Bebyggelseregistret|publisher= [[Swedish National Heritage Board]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n| designated date        = \n| architect              = Donatus<br>[[Adam van D\u00fcren]]<br>[[Carl Georg Brunius]]<br>[[Helgo Zettervall]]\n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = \n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n\n| capacity               = \n| length                 = {{convert|85|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width                  = {{convert|30|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width nave             = \n| height                 = {{convert|55|m|ft}} (to the top of the towers){{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}\n| diameter               = \n| other dimensions       = \n| floor area             = \n| dome quantity          = \n| dome height outer      = \n| dome height inner      = \n| dome dia outer         = \n| dome dia inner         = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           = \n| materials              = \n\n| diocese                = [[Diocese of Lund]]\n| bishop                 = [[Johan Tyrberg]]\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                = \n}}\n'''Lund Cathedral''' ({{lang-sv|Lunds domkyrka}}) is a [[cathedral]] of the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Church of Sweden]] in [[Lund]], [[Scania]], Sweden. It is the seat of the [[List of bishops of Lund|Bishop of Lund]] and the main church of the [[Diocese of Lund]]. It was built as the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] cathedral of the [[archiepiscopal see]] of all the [[Nordic countries]], dedicated to [[Lawrence of Rome|Saint Lawrence]]. It is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.\n\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the most powerful representative of [[Romanesque architecture]] in the Nordic countries\". At the time of its construction, Lund and the cathedral belonged to Denmark. The main altar was consecrated in 1145 and the cathedral was by that time largely finished; the western towers were built somewhat later. Its architecture show clear influences from contemporary north Italian architecture, conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]]. The earliest architect was named Donatus, though his precise role in the construction of the cathedral is difficult to determine. The new cathedral was richly decorated with stone sculpture, including two unusual statues in the crypt traditionally called \"[[Fin (troll)|The giant Finn and his wife]]\" about which a local legend has developed. The cathedral was severely damaged in a fire in 1234, and major restoration works were carried out in the early 16th century under the leadership of [[Adam van D\u00fcren]]. Following the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]], the cathedral suffered from lost income and dilapidation. In 1658, the city of Lund and the cathedral became a part of Sweden following the [[Treaty of Roskilde]]. Lund Cathedral was the site of the ceremony founding [[Lund University]] in 1668. Repairs were made during the 18th century but in 1832 a complete restoration of the cathedral was recommended. Subsequently much of the cathedral was restored and rebuilt during most of the 19th century. The work was first led by [[Carl Georg Brunius]] and later by architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] and not entirely finished until 1893. The changes implemented during the 19th century were extensive; among other things, Zettervall had the entire western part, including the towers, demolished and rebuilt to his own designs.\n\nThe medieval cathedral contains several historic furnishings and works of art. Its main altarpiece was donated to the cathedral in 1398, and it also contains [[Gothic art|Gothic]] choir stalls, bronzes and an [[astronomical clock]] from the 15th century (although heavily restored in 1923). When it was built, Lund Cathedral was lavishly decorated with Romanesque stone sculptures. It also contains late medieval stone sculptures from the time of Adam van D\u00fcren's renovation. After the Reformation the cathedral was also equipped with a decorated [[pulpit]]. Of more recent date is the large [[mosaic]] in the [[apse]], by [[Joakim Skovgaard]], installed in 1927. Lund Cathedral has six [[church organ]]s, one of which is the largest in Sweden, and is also used as a concert venue.\n\n==Historical background==\nChristian missionaries from present-day Germany and England were active in the [[Christianization of Scandinavia|Christianisation of Denmark]], and Denmark eventually became part of the [[Prince-Archbishopric of Bremen|Archdiocese of Hamburg-Bremen]]. Lund was at the time part of Denmark. With the consolidation of Danish monarchy during the second half of the 11th century, and with a political crisis in continental Europe, there arose an opportunity for the Danish monarchs to bypass the German influence over church policy in Denmark.{{sfn|Ryd\u00e9n|1999|p=99\u2013100}} An [[episcopal see]] was created in Lund in 1060.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25}} At the same time, another see was created in [[Dalby, Lund Municipality|Dalby]], very close to Lund. However, when the first bishop of Lund ([[Henry of Lund]]) died, the erstwhile bishop of Dalby, [[Egino (Bishop of Dalby)|Egino]], was installed in Lund and Dalby abandoned as the seat of a bishop. At the same time, in 1103, Lund was proclaimed an archiepiscopal see overseeing all Nordic countries.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25\u201329}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=4\u20135}}\n\nSome kind of rudimentary settlement probably existed at the site of Lund Cathedral at the end of the 10th and early 11th centuries, but no remains of buildings have been found there.{{sfn|Cinthio|1990|p=1}} Lund Cathedral is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=7}} During the [[Middle Ages]], the cathedral was surrounded by several buildings serving the diocese, of which only [[Liberiet]], which at one point served as a library, survives.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=69\u201371}}\n\n==History==\n===Foundation and construction===\n[[File:Lund domkyrka - crypt (by Pudelek).JPG|thumb|right|The [[crypt]], the oldest part of Lund Cathedral]]\n[[File:Lund Dom Chor.JPG|thumb|right|The [[apse]] is the most well-preserved part of the original exterior]]\nThe earliest written mention of a church in Lund dedicated to [[Saint Lawrence]] \u2014 the patron saint of Lund Cathedral during the Middle Ages \u2014 dates from 1085.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=37}} Slightly later sources mention both a new and an old church dedicated to Saint Lawrence.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=38}} During the 1940s, archaeological excavations in the cathedral uncovered the foundations of another church inside the present building. The exact age, shape and function of this predecessor to the cathedral has been a matter of some debate.{{sfn|Cinthio|1957|p=1\u201342}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=62\u201364}} Most scholars believe that construction of a church on the site of Lund Cathedral was begun sometime during the second half of the 11th century.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} Some time thereafter a new church was begun in almost the same place, but to a larger design in the form of the present cathedral. Parts of the earlier church may have been incorporated in the walls of the cathedral.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} The decision to abandon Dalby as a [[bishopric]] and make Lund the sole archbishopric in Scandinavia may have prompted the change of plans.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=40}}\n\nApart from the obscurity which thus surrounds the very beginning of the history of the cathedral, the construction of Lund Cathedral is probably among the most well documented among any [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque churches]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} Two contemporary accounts of the building of the cathedral, in the form of the [[illuminated manuscripts]] ''{{ill|Necrologium Lundense|sv}}'' and ''{{ill|Liber daticus vetustior|sv}}'', are still preserved in the library of [[Lund University]]. Both books contain notes, written in [[Latin language|Latin]], with dates of the progression of the construction. The oldest part of the cathedral is the large [[crypt]]. Its main [[altar]] was inaugurated on 30 June 1123, followed by the north (1126) and south (1131) side altars of the crypt. Only then did the cathedral begin to be used.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} One of the main functions of the crypt appears to have been as a place where [[baptism]]s were conducted.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=4}} The main altar of the cathedral was dedicated to [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Saint Mary]] and Saint Lawrence in 1145, by the second archbishop of Lund, [[Eskil of Lund|Eskil]], in a ceremony attended by bishops from present-day Germany, Denmark and Sweden.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=29\u201330}} By then, the construction of the cathedral to more or less its present dimensions was complete.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2004|p=186\u2013187}}\n\nUnusually for that time, the architect of the cathedral is known by his name, Donatus.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=164}} The name appears in both the ''Necrologium Lundense'' (as \"Donatus architectus\") and the ''Liber daticus vetustior''. Donatus may have been responsible for the layout of the crypt and the cathedral above ground as far west as the current north and south portals of the cathedral, although it is difficult to draw any definitive conclusions about his precise role.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}} The same is true for his successor, possibly a builder named Ragnar.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=32}} The building erected during the time of Donatus and his successor show clear influences from Romanesque architecture in [[Lombardy]], conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} Donatus himself appears to have been from, or at least educated in, Lombardy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=58}} [[Speyer Cathedral]] in western Germany is stylistically closely related to Lund Cathedral (especially the crypt), and it has been proposed that Donatus came to Lund from Speyer, where construction more or less ceased in 1106 following the death of [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry IV]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=59}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=148}} Similarities have also frequently been pointed out between Lund Cathedral and [[Mainz Cathedral]], and the design of the apse is similar to that of the [[Basilica of Saint Servatius]] in [[Maastricht]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} On a more general level, the origins of the style of Lund Cathedral can be found in [[Basilica of Sant'Ambrogio]] ([[Milan]]), [[Modena Cathedral]] and several churches in [[Pavia]], all in northern Italy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Similar stylistic influences can be seen in other cathedrals in Denmark from the same time, for example in [[Ribe Cathedral]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}}\n\nThe building of Lund Cathedral must have involved a large number of people and was a collective undertaking.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} Comparable but somewhat later workshops at [[Cologne Cathedral]] and [[Uppsala Cathedral]] employed a workforce of about 100 and 60 people, respectively.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The project was instrumental in establishing a workshop where local craftsmen could be educated, and thus disseminating artistic influences from continental Europe to Scandinavia. The stone sculptors {{ill|Carl stenm\u00e4stare|sv}}, {{ill|M\u00e5rten stenm\u00e4stare|sv}} and [[Majestatis]] were probably all Scandinavians who were educated at the construction site.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Many early Romanesque stone churches in the countryside, particularly in Scania but also in the rest of Sweden, show direct influences from Lund Cathedral, notably {{ill|V\u00e4 Church|sv|V\u00e4 kyrka}} (Scania).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=79\u201381}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=265\u2013281}} Other examples are e.g. {{ill|Lannaskede Old Church|sv|Lannaskede gamla kyrka}} ([[Sm\u00e5land]]), {{ill|Hogstad Church|sv|Hogstads kyrka}} ([[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]]) and [[Havdhem Church]] ([[Gotland]]).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=90\u201392}}\n\n===Fire and repairs===\nThe plan and layout of the building consecrated in 1145 was similar to the one seen today. A noticeable difference was that the entire choir was separated from the nave by a wall and reserved for the clergy. The towers were also not built until a few decades later.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=52}} The intention was probably to provide the cathedral with [[vault (architecture)|vaults]], but instead a flat wooden ceiling was installed.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68\u201369}} The cathedral was adorned with [[Church murals in Sweden|wall paintings]] and almost certainly by [[Medieval stained glass in Sweden|stained glass windows]], but none of these remain.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} In 1234, the cathedral was heavily damaged by a large fire.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=78}} Large donations were made to the church in the following years, to allow for repairs.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=74}} Even so, the need for  repairs was continuous for the entire 13th century.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80}} Following the fire, the burnt-out ceiling was replaced by [[brick]] vaults.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}} Changes were also made to the layout of the westernmost part of the building.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76}} A conflict erupted between King [[Christopher I of Denmark]] and Archbishop [[Jakob Erlandsen]] in 1257 partially because the choir had been enlarged and the seats of the royal family moved, itself a testimony of the growing power of the Church.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76\u201378}} Two [[chapel]]s were added to the cathedral during the 14th and 15th centuries; one located adjacent to the two westernmost [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] of the south aisle of the nave, and the other as a southern extension of the east transept.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80\u201381}} [[Buttress]]es were also added piecemeal to the building during the 13th and 14th centuries, to stabilise the building which was under strain from the new, heavier vaults, the added chapels and the constant ringing of the 8.5 [[tonne]] [[church bell]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=86\u201387}}\n\n===Changes by Adam van D\u00fcren and later===\n[[File:Lunds domkyrka - KMB - 16001000533737.jpg|thumb|right|A drawing of the cathedral as it appeared in 1750]]\nThe German sculptor and builder [[Adam van D\u00fcren]] apparently worked intermittently at restoring and altering the cathedral between {{circa}} 1506 or 1507 and 1524.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=90\u201391}} Despite, and to some extent because of, the work that had been done during the preceding centuries since the great fire of 1234, the cathedral was in need of a thorough restoration.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=87}} Adam van D\u00fcren and his workshop made several changes and contributions. A new drainage system was installed in the crypt, and as part of that work a [[well]], which probably replaced an earlier well in the same location, was decorated with [[satire|satirical]] [[allegory|allegories]].{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=88\u201395}} The workshop of van D\u00fcren also created two new windows in the choir, built a large buttress to support the southern transept (before 1513), and rebuilt the [[gable]] of the northern transept (1524) as well as its vaults. New and considerably larger windows with [[Pointed arch (architecture)|pointed arches]] were installed in both the northern wall of the north transept and in the southern wall of the south transept.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=100}} The towers and western facade were also repaired in 1512\u201318 and again in 1527.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=91}} It has been argued that the cathedral may have collapsed, were it not for the work done by van D\u00fcren.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=104}}\n\nFollowing the Reformation in the 16th century, the diocese lost much of its revenues.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=126}} The building was still subjected to much stress, not least by the use of the large church bell, and suffered during the recurrent [[List of wars involving Denmark|wars between Denmark and Sweden]]; in 1658 Lund permanently became part of Sweden. Despite van D\u00fcren's repairs, the church was described as being \"very dilapidated\" in 1682.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128}} During the 18th century, the chapels of the church were used for funerals, but also as an improvised [[morgue]] where corpses were occasionally left for several years.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=130}} Attempts at repairs were made; among them the entire apse was dismantled and then re-erected.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}} Many of the repairs were however either temporary or outright detrimental to condition of the building. King [[Gustav III of Sweden]] visited the cathedral crypt in 1785 and expressed his displeasure at its state.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=132}} In 1812, the aforementioned chapels from the 14th and 15th centuries were demolished.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}}\n\n===Changes by Carl Georg Brunius and Helgo Zettervall===\n[[File:Demolition of the tower of Lund Cathedral.jpg|thumb|right|Demolition of the south tower of the cathedral during the time of [[Helgo Zettervall]]]]\nWhen the congregation wanted to build a new [[church organ]] in the early 19th century, architect {{ill|Axel Nystr\u00f6m|sv|Axel Nystr\u00f6m (1793\u20131868)}} was invited to examine the structure in 1832. Nystr\u00f6m recommended a complete renovation of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}} The chairman of the council in charge of administering the cathedral buildings, [[Carl Georg Brunius]], was called to execute the plans of Nystr\u00f6m, and he did so while at the same time making changes according to his own convictions. He also wrote the first systematic art history of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} Brunius had the organ moved, the crypt repaired, installed a set of steps connecting the choir with the nave and improved the drainage system.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} He also removed modern furnishings, re-built some of the buttresses and changed the stone of a large part of the facade.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121}} Brunius retired due to old age in 1859, but as there was still a substantial need for repairs, the young architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] was appointed to carry out the rest of the work in 1860.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013122}} A conflict between Brunius and Zettervall developed almost immediately, but Zettervall would keep working on restoring the cathedral until 1893 and ultimately managed to implement most of his ideas for the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013181}} A compromise in 1862 proposed that the Danish architect [[Ferdinand Meldahl]] would assume the main responsibility, and Zettervall would merely assist Meldahl. However, it soon became apparent that Zettervall would not accept a subordinate role and Meldahl himself showed little interest in the project.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=141}} In 1862, Zettervall traveled extensively through Germany and Italy to study stylistically related architecture, and also to visit the latest examples of building restoration so that he could draw upon that experience in his work at Lund.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=134\u2013141}} In 1863, he presented a first proposal for a complete restoration of the cathedral. Zettervall himself considered it a \"reasonable middle ground between reparation and reconstruction\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142}} The proposal would mean the removal of all buttresses, a new roof, completely rebuilt towers, and the removal of the large Gothic windows in the transepts. Zettervall also proposed to add an octagonal dome over the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]]. Far-reaching changes would also affect the interior. In the proposal Zettervall strove to reduce and refine the building volumes of the cathedral and create a unified composition of block-like elements.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142\u2212152}}\n\nThe proposal by Zettervall was criticised, not least by Meldahl. Zettervall re-worked the proposal and put forward a revised, less far-reaching proposal in 1864, notably without the central dome.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=152}} This proposal was also rejected and the plan for a complete overhaul abandoned; however it was at the same time decided that Zettervall would continue working on repairing the cathedral and every year make what changes that were deemed necessary. In this way, Zettervall could piecemeal over the next decades to rebuild the cathedral largely in line with his design from 1864.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=158\u2013159}}\n\nBetween 1832 and 1893, the cathedral was radically transformed by the work of Brunius and Zettervall. All windows were replaced, several vaults and pillars were repaired or rebuilt, and both architects effected extensive changes to the transept. Just as he had suggested, Zettervall had all the buttresses removed and demolished the entire western part of the church, including the towers, and rebuilt them according to his own [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Neo-Romanesque]] designs.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13\u201314}}<ref name=byggnaden>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/byggnaden/|title= En kyrka i st\u00e4ndig f\u00f6r\u00e4ndring|trans-title= A constantly changing church|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 20th century, archaeological excavations were carried out in and around the cathedral. The building also underwent a major restoration in 1954\u20131963, led by architect {{ill|Eiler Gr\u00e6be|sv}}. During this time the decorative painting from the 19th century was removed.<ref name=byggnaden/> The large [[mosaic]] decorating the apse was installed in 1927, and designed by [[Joakim Skovgaard]].{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=14}} In 1990, the layout of the choir was changed and the altar placed in the crossing.<ref name=byggnaden/> [[Pope Francis]] visited the cathedral on 31 October 2016 to observe the 499th anniversary of the beginning of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Christina|title=Pope Francis, in Sweden, Urges Catholic-Lutheran Reconciliation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/01/world/europe/pope-francis-in-sweden-urges-catholic-lutheran-reconciliation.html|accessdate=1 November 2016|work=The New York Times|date=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and decoration==\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the most powerful representative of Romanesque architecture in the Nordic countries\".{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} It lies at some distance from any other buildings and dominates its surroundings.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=181}} It consists of the two towers built by Zettervall, which flank the main entrance to the west. Behind them a [[nave]] with two [[aisle]]s open up to a [[transept]] that is somewhat higher than the nave. A short flight of stairs thus connect the nave with the [[choir (architecture)|choir]] as well as with the crypt under the choir. The choir ends in an apse. Inside, the bays of the cathedral are supported by [[groin vault]]s. The number of bays in the aisles are the double of that in the nave. The arches that separate the nave from the aisles are supported by piers and pillars of alternating width. The crypt has over forty shallow [[groin vault]]s supported by pillars with cushion-cap capitals. It is sparsely lit by low small windows.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=45}}\n\nSeen from outside, the different elements of the building are clearly discernible as independent volumes, \"as if they could be taken apart and put together again\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=181}} The apse of the cathedral is a \"forcefully articulated\" semi-circle of three storeys.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The apse is the most well-preserved part of the Romanesque building and has been described as \"the artistic high point of the exterior\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=124}} The southern portal of the nave is perhaps the oldest of the cathedral. Five decorated [[archivolt]]s supported by small columns with variously decorated [[capital (architecture)|capitals]], frame a [[tympanon]] depicting the [[Lamb of God]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=70\u201371}} The northern portal is slightly later and more richly decorated. Its tympanon depicts [[Samson]] wrestling with the lion.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=72\u201373}} Two bronze doors built by {{ill|Carl Johan Dyfverman|sv|Carl Johan Dyfverman (konstn\u00e4r)}} serve as the main entrance in the centre of the west facade. They have 24 reliefs with subjects from the Bible, particularly the Old Testament. Above the doorway, the tympanon depicts [[Christ]], [[Canute IV of Denmark]] and Saint Lawrence.<ref name=byggnaden/> The cathedral has two [[sacristy|sacristies]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}} The building material of the cathedral is mostly [[sandstone]] quarried in the area around [[H\u00f6\u00f6r]]. The main walls are constructed as shells of sandstone filled with [[fieldstone]] mixed with [[lime mortar]]. The thickness of the walls is around {{convert|2 to 3|m|ft}}.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=126\u2013127}} \n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Overview of Lund Cathedral\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Lunds domkyrka. Plan.png|Plan\nFile:Lunds domkyrka\u2013flygbild 06 september 2014.jpg|Aerial view from the south east\nFile:Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17 4.jpg|View from the entrance towards east\nFile:Lund cathedral interior 2015-03-30-4746.jpg|View from the altar towards west\n</gallery>\n\n===Sculptures===\n[[File:Finn the Giant, Lund Cathedral crypt 2017-08-17 1.jpg|thumb|right|\"[[Fin (troll)|The giant Finn and his wife]]\" in the crypt, probably a depiction of the biblical hero [[Samson]]]]\nWhen it comes to stone sculpture, Lund Cathedral was the most lavishly decorated Romanesque building to be built in the Nordic countries according to art historian {{ill|Jan Svanberg|sv}}.{{sfn|Svanberg|1995|p=152}} Perhaps the most well-known and striking of these are the sculptures of two figures traditionally called \"[[Fin (troll)|The giant Finn and his wife]]\" in the crypt.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} According to a local legend, the giant helped build the cathedral, and when he was not payed for his services he tried to destroy it by shaking the pillars, but was petrified.<ref name=finn>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/jatten-finn/|title= J\u00e4tten Finn vakar \u00f6ver kryptan|trans-title= The giant Finn watches over the crypt|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The larger of the two figures is embracing a column, while the smaller is attached to another column with a rope. These sculptures have probably been the subject of more attempts at an explanation than any other medieval artworks in Sweden, according to art historian Mereth Lindgren.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}} Most scholars today believe the larger sculpture depicts [[Samson]], but what the smaller figure is supposed to represent is not known. The sculptures date from the construction of the crypt but have been treated poorly, especially during the 18th century, and lost much of their original detailing.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}}\n\nThe fluted columns also found in the crypt are similar in style to [[Norman architecture|English Norman architecture]] and may indicate that the very first artistic influences came from the area bordering the [[English Channel]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64\u201365}} Apart from these columns however, the rich stone ornamentation is clearly [[wikt:Lombardic|Lombardic]] in style, meaning related to north Italian art of the period.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} Among these is a [[baldachin]] now immured in the east wall of the north transept which may have been part of the original western facade; Its columns have [[Corinthian order|Corinthian capitals]] and support a richly decorated archivolt on which traces of original paint survives. Opposite, in the south wall, is a smaller baldachin where the columns themselves are sculpted angels (one with [[feather tights]]) standing on lions. Similar sculptures exist in [[Como]] and Modena in northern Italy.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=74\u201375}} In addition, the capitals of the columns in the church are all of high [[wikt:artisanal|artisanal]] quality, and can be broadly divided into two groups displaying either [[Classical architecture|Classical]] or [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine]] influences.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} Apart from its rich Romanesque decoration, Lund Cathedral also contains several late medieval sculptures made by Adam van D\u00fcren, as mentioned above. Several of these are of animals and contain inscriptions in [[Low German]]. A relief in the south transept displaying the [[Woman of the Apocalypse]] flanked by Saint Lawrence and Saint Canute is similar to the portal relief van D\u00fcren made a couple of years earlier at [[Glimmingehus]].{{sfn|Svanberg|1996|p=196\u2013197}}\n\n===Altarpiece===\nThe medieval main [[altarpiece]] was donated to the cathedral in 1398 by [[Ide Pedersdatter Falk]].<ref name=kor>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/hogkoret/|title= Gyllene mosaik och korstolar fr\u00e5n 1300-talet|trans-title= Golden mosaics and choir stalls from the 14th century|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The altarpiece is stylistically similar to a group of altarpieces from northern Germany. Its central panel depicts the [[Coronation of the Virgin]], surrounded by two rows of 40 saints, 26 of which are original. Twelve figures have been taken from other medieval altarpieces, while two of the added figures are from the 17th century. The altarpiece is {{convert|7.6|m|ft}} wide but is missing an original pair of wings.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=20\u201323}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=112\u2013113}}\n\n===Choir stalls===\n[[File:Lunds Domkyrka korstolar h\u00f6ger om koret.JPG|thumb|right|The right side of the choir, showing parts of the choir stalls (right) and the main altarpiece (left)]]\nThe choir contains two rows of medieval choir stalls containing in total 78 seats. The wooden stalls date from the end of the 14th century, probably commissioned by archbishop Nils J\u00f6nson some time between 1361 and 1379. Clearly made by several different wood carvers, they are approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall without their gables and decorated with carved details. These are biblical scenes from both the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]], but the stalls also contain [[misericord]]s portraying animals and other small details. Their style is [[Gothic art|High Gothic]] and they are stylistically linked with contemporary art from the Rhine Valley. They are among the largest wooden Gothic sculptures to survive in the Nordic countries, and have been described as being of internationally high quality.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}} The choir stalls in Lund Cathedral also lent stylistic inspiration to the choir stalls in [[Roskilde Cathedral]] and [[St. Bendt's Church, Ringsted]].{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}}{{sfn|Dun\u00e9r|1984|p=1\u20139}}\n\nSlightly older than the choir stalls is a [[Cathedra|bishop's throne]] which survives in a damaged state and is placed in the south transept. It is somewhat similar in construction to the choir stalls but stylistically different and more closely related to contemporary art from north Germany.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=32\u201335}} Currently placed next to the bishop's chair is also a Gothic [[Church tabernacle|tabernacle]] in the form of a {{convert|5|m|ft}} tall, decorated wooden pillar. It contains two cabinets surmounted by a statuette of a female saint and crowned by a hexagonal spire. The tabernacle was repaired by Brunius in the 19th century. The saint may  be {{ill|Ida von Toggenburg|de}}.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=36\u201337}}\n\n===Astronomical clock===\n{{Main|Horologium mirabile Lundense}}\n[[File:Lunds astronomiska ur-2.jpg|thumb|right|The [[astronomical clock]]]]\nThe [[astronomical clock]] of Lund Cathedral, presently located at the west end of the north aisle, dates from the late Middle Ages and was installed in Lund Cathedral {{circa}} 1425. In 1837, it was dismantled. It was restored at the initiative of architect {{ill|Theodor W\u00e5hlin|sv}} and the Danish clock-maker Julius Bertram Larsen and re-inaugurated in 1923. The upper part, which is original, is the clock, while the lower part, a reconstruction, is a calendar. Twice every day the two knights on the top clash their swords. The clock then plays the tune ''[[In dulci jubilo]]'' and a procession of figures parades across the face of the clock.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=125\u2013126}} Three astronomical clocks of similar design are preserved in Europe. The clock in Lund was repaired 2009\u20132010.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}<ref name=svt>{{cite web |url= https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/skane/lund-uret-i-domkyrkan-slutar-sla|title= Lund \u2013 Uret i domkyrkan slutar sl\u00e5|trans-title= The clock in  the cathedral ceases to strike|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 12 October 2009|website= |publisher= [[Sveriges television]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref><ref name=uret>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/uret/|title= Det underbara uret i Lund|trans-title= The astonishing clock in Lund|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nA decorated conventional clock from 1623 is immured on the opposite side of the nave, in the west wall of the south aisle.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=126}}\n\n===Bronzes===\nThe cathedral also owns three High Gothic [[bronze]] columns carrying statuettes and a seven-branched candelabrum from the end of the Middle Ages. Two of the bronze columns are crowned by angels, and the third one by a statuette of Saint Lawrence, holding a gridiron, the symbol of his martyrdom. It probably dates from the middle of the 14th century, while the two angel-bearing columns may be somewhat later. Saint Lawrence's column is approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall (and the saint {{convert|70|cm|inch}}), while the columns with angels are slightly smaller.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114}} The three columns were probably made in [[L\u00fcbeck]] or [[Hamburg]]. Presently located in the south transept is also the {{convert|3.5|m|ft}} tall seven-branched candelabrum or candle holder from the late 15th century, manufactured by Harmen Bonstede in Hamburg.<ref name=stake>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/sjuarmade-ljusstakens-kapell/|title= V\u00e5r tids martyrer och den sjuarmade ljusstaken|trans-title= The martyrs of our time and the seven-branched candelabrum|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> It was supplied to the cathedral in a dismantled state, and traces of its assembly instruction are still discernible on the candelabrum. Similar candelabra were installed in a number of Scandinavian cathedrals at approximately the same time; although the one in Lund is larger than those in the cathedrals of [[Aarhus Cathedral|Aarhus]], Ribe, [[Viborg Cathedral|Viborg]] and [[Storkyrkan|Stockholm]].<ref name=stake/>{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114\u2013116}}\n\n===Pulpit===\nThe current [[pulpit]] was commissioned at the end of the 16th century and is marked with the date 1592. The artist was [[Johannes Ganssog]] from [[Frankfurt an der Oder]] in present-day Germany. It is attached with unusual technical skill to one of the pillars of the nave, and it is entered through a stair cut inside the pillar. The building material is sandstone, black [[limestone]] and black and white [[marble]], and it is partially painted and [[gilding|gilded]]. Reliefs of [[alabaster]] on the side show scenes from the New Testament.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=60\u201364}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}\n\n===Graves and funerary monuments===\n[[File:Herman af Slesvig (gravsten).JPG|thumb|right|The grave of Hermann, [[List of the bishops of Schleswig|bishop of Schleswig]], 12th century, the oldest grave in the crypt]]\nThe crypt contains the oldest grave in the cathedral, the grave of Hermann, [[List of the bishops of Schleswig|bishop of Schleswig]], who played an important role as an emissary of archbishop Eskil of Lund during the negotiations to establish Lund as an independent archdiocese. The simple Romanesque [[sarcophagus]], which has an inscription in Latin and a depiction of the bishop, is located in the apse of the crypt. It dates from the middle of the 12th century.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=46}} The crypt also contains the much larger grave monument of the last archbishop, {{ill|Birger Gunnersen|sv}}, which is centrally placed in the crypt. It is of a kind which is not unusual in continental Europe but very unusual in the Nordic countries: a large stone sarcophagus decorated on all sides with sculptures in high relief and with a full-scale depiction of the bishop in full dress on the lid. It was made by Adam van D\u00fcren in 1512.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=94}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=48\u201349}} The cathedral's largest grave monument is that of bishop [[Hans Brostorp]], who died in 1497 and who during his lifetime inaugurated the [[University of Copenhagen]]. The monument is made of limestone from [[Gotland]] and decorated in low relief.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=47}}\n\nThe nave and the aisles contain several memorial plaques and [[epitaph]]s. Several commemorate bishops, such as {{ill|Johan Engestr\u00f6m|sv}} (1699\u20131777) and {{ill|Nils Hessl\u00e9n|sv}} (1728\u20131811). Many others were made for professors at Lund University, e.g. {{ill|Eberhard Rosenblad|sv}} (1714\u20131796) and {{ill|Erasmus Sack|sv}} (1633\u20131697). The oldest epitaph of the cathedral commemorates the owner of [[Krageholm Castle]] {{ill|Lave Brahe|sv}} (1500\u20131567) and his wife [[G\u00f6rvel Fadersdotter (Sparre)]] (1509 or 1517 \u2013 1605).{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=122\u2013125}}\n\n===Baptismal font===\nThe [[baptismal font]] of the cathedral is a sparsely decorated Early Gothic font made of reddish grey limestone.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}\n\n==Flora==\n[[File:Flickr - Sigfrid Lundberg - Wall-rue, Asplenium ruta-muraria.jpg|thumb|right|[[Asplenium ruta-muraria|Wall-rue]] growing on the [[apse]]]]\nSeveral surveys and descriptions of the [[flora]] of the cathedral, like the plants that grow on its walls, have been made. The first to describe the flora of the cathedral was [[Daniel Rolander]], one of the [[apostles of Linnaeus]], who made a list of the [[vascular plant]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]] he found growing on the building in 1771.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} It was rediscovered in the 20th century and published in 1931. [[Elias Magnus Fries]] also made observations about the flora of the cathedral during the first half of the 19th century. More systematic surveys of the flora of the building have been published in 1922 and in 1993 (the latter only encompassing lichen).{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} Of the species observed growing on the cathedral, the minute [[fern]] [[Asplenium ruta-muraria|wall-rue]] was mentioned as early as 1756 by {{ill|Anders Tidstr\u00f6m|sv}} and is perhaps the most conspicuous member of the cathedral flora.{{sfn|Gertz|1923|p=458}} When the lichen flora was surveyed in 1993, 15 species were discovered. One of these, ''[[Lecanora perpruinosa]]'', had not been observed in the province of Scania before.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=26}}\n\n==Relationship with Lund University==\nThe founding of [[Lund University]] was acknowledged in a ceremony in the cathedral in 1668.<ref name=nyckeltal>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/nyckelartal/|title= Ett p\u00e4rlband av h\u00e4ndelser|trans-title= A string of events|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> Following the Reformation, the choir was used for a long time as a classroom, first by [[Lund Cathedral School]] and later by the university. The university also used the choir to store its [[library]] for some time.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128\u2013129}} The cathedral is still the place for the ceremony of the [[wikt:conferment|conferment]] of new doctor's degrees at the university.<ref name=universitet>{{cite web |url= https://www.lu.se/om-universitetet/akademiska-hogtider/doktorspromotionen/promotionsdagen|title= Promotionsdagen|trans-title= The day of conferment of the doctor's degree|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= [[Lund University]]|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe cathedral has five [[choir (music)|choirs]] for adults and two choirs for children.<ref name=korer>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/musik-kultur/korer-2/|title= K\u00f6rer|trans-title= Choirs|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The cathedral is also frequently used for concerts.<ref name=konserter>{{cite web |url=https://lundsdomkyrka.se/musik-kultur/konserter/|title= Konserter varje vecka|trans-title= Concerts every week|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 23 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThere are currently six church organs in Lund Cathedral, including the largest church organ in Sweden. The gallery organ was built between 1932 and 1934 by the Danish company [[Marcussen & S\u00f8n]] and renovated by the same company in 1992. It has 102 stops distributed between four manuals and a pedalboard. There are 7,074 pipes in total. The smallest organ is inside the astronomical clock, where it plays ''In dulci jubilo''.<ref name=orglar>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/orglar/|title= Sex orglar i Domkyrkan|trans-title= Six organs in the cathedral|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last= Bodin|first= Anders|date= 2017|title= Helgo Zettervalls arkitektur: kyrkor|volume=II|trans-title= The architecture of Helgo Zettervall: churches|url= http://kth.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1094819/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Carlssons bokf\u00f6rlag|isbn=9789173317856}}\n*{{cite book |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1957|title= Lunds domkyrka under romansk tid|trans-title= Lund Cathedral during the Romanesque era|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/21557081/Diss_Erik_Cinthio.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1990|title= Lunds domkyrkas f\u00f6rhistoria. S:t Laurentiuspatrociniet och Knut den Heliges kyrka \u00e4n en g\u00e5ng|trans-title= The pre-history of Lund Cathedral. The patronage of St. Lawrence and the church of Canute the Holy once more|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1990-2_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 2|issue= |pages= 1\u201313|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Dun\u00e9r|first= Uno|date= 1984|title= Gideon och ullen|trans-title= Gideon and the wool|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1984-3_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 3|issue= |pages= 1\u201310|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Gertz|first= Otto|date= 1923|title= Vegetationen \u00e5 ruinerna av Alvastra klosterkyrka|trans-title= The vegetation on the ruins of Alvastra monastery church|url= |language= Swedish|journal= Botaniska notiser|volume= |issue= |pages= 457\u2013463|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Johansson|first= Per|date= 1993|title= Lavfloran p\u00e5 Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The lichen flora of Lund Cathedral|url= http://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1203014/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Svensk Botanisk Tidskrift|volume= |issue= 87|pages= 25\u201330|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Karlsson|editor1-first=Lennart|last= Lindgren|first= Mereth|date= 1995|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den romanska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenarkitekturen|trans-chapter=The stone architecture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0}}\n*{{cite book |last= Rydbeck|first= Otto|date= 1915|title= Bidrag till Lunds domkyrkas byggnadshistoria|trans-title= Contributions to the building history of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694254|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= Newman|editor1-first= Ernst|last= Rydbeck|first= Otto|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrkas historia 1145\u20131945|trans-title= History of Lund Cathedral 1145\u20131945|chapter= Lunds domkyrka, byggnadens och dess inventariers historia enligt de nyaste forskningsresultaten|trans-chapter= Lund Cathedral, the history of the building and its furnishings according to the latest research|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/8073961|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Svenska kyrkans diakonistyrelses bokf\u00f6rlag}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|editor1-first= Claes|last= Ryd\u00e9n|first= Thomas|date= 1998|title= Metropolis Daniae: ett stycke Europa|trans-title= Metropolis Daniae: a piece of Europe|chapter= Lunds domkyrka, det universella rummet|trans-chapter= Lund Cathedral, the universal space|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/63935286/Ryden_LundsDomkyrkaUniversellaRummet.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Lund University|issn=0454-5915}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= L\u00f6fvendahl|editor1-first= Runo|editor2-last= Sundn\u00e9r|editor2-first= Barbro|last= Sundn\u00e9r|first= Barbro|date= 1997|title= Lunds domkyrka: stenmaterial och skadebild|trans-title= Lund Cathedral: stone material and damages|chapter= Byggnadshistoria|trans-chapter= Building history|url= http://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1289650/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Riksantikvarie\u00e4mbetet ([[Swedish National Heritage Board]])|isbn=91-7209-006-5}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Karlsson|editor1-first=Lennart|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1995|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den romanska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Augustsson|editor1-first=Jan-Erik|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1996|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den gotiska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Gothic art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1915|title= Konstverk i Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= Art in Lund Cathedral|url= https://archive.org/details/konstverkilundsd00wran/mode/2up|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1923|title= Lunds domkyrkas konsthistoria: f\u00f6rbindelser och stilfr\u00e4nder|trans-title= The art history of Lund Cathedral: connections and stylistic equals|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/416081|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|first= Claes|date= 2014|title= Sk\u00e5nes kyrkor 1050-1949|trans-title= The churches of Sk\u00e5ne 1050\u20131949|language=Swedish|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/18066221|location= K\u00e4vlinge|publisher= Domus Propria|isbn= 978-91-637-5874-4}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last= Brunius|first= Carl Georg|date= 1836|title= Nordens \u00e4ldsta metropolitankyrka, eller, historisk och arkitektonisk beskrifning \u00f6fver Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The oldest metropolitan church in the Nordic countries, or, historic and architectonic description of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694639|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Berling}}\n*{{cite book |last= Gierow|first= Krister|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrka i litteraturen: bibliografisk f\u00f6rteckning|trans-title= Lund Cathedral in literature: a bibliography|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/1186054}}\n*{{cite book |last= Zettervall|first= Helgo|date= 1916|title= Helgo Zettervall om Lunds domkyrka: en byggnadsbeskrivning i brev|trans-title= Helgo Zettervall on Lund Cathedral: description of a building in letters|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/10258926|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Lunds domkyrka|Lund Cathedral}}\n* [https://lundsdomkyrka.se/ Official website of the cathedral]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A14714&dswid=3243 Digitised copy of the ''Necrologium Lundense'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A13276&dswid=7054 Digitised copy of the ''Liber daticus vetustior'', with information about the book and its contents in English]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3LzcTh1FX5k3C8Y4EJI0Ew YouTube channel of the cathedral]\n\n{{Churches in Scania}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1145]]\n[[Category:12th-century churches]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lund]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in pre-Reformation Sweden]]\n[[Category:Lutheran cathedrals in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Romanesque architecture in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Lund]]\n[[Category:Coronation church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Sk\u00e5ne County]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Diocese of Lund]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Lund Cathedral\n| fullname               = \n| image                  = Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17.jpg\n| imagesize              = \n| imagelink              = \n| imagealt               = \n| caption                = View of Lund Cathedral from the south east\n| coordinates            = {{coord|55|42|15|N|13|11|36|E|region:SE_type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| osgraw                 = \n| osgridref              = \n| location               = [[Lund]]\n| country                = [[Sweden]]\n\n| denomination           = [[Church of Sweden]]\n| previous denomination  = [[Church of Denmark]] (until 1658)<br>[[Catholic Church]] (until the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]])\n| churchmanship          = \n| membership             = \n| attendance             = \n| website                = [http://www.lundsdomkyrka.se/ Website of the Cathedral]\n\n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| founded date           = Late 11th century\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = \n| dedicated date         = \n| consecrated date       = 1123 (crypt)<br>1145 (main altar)\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = \n| past bishop            = \n| people                 = \n\n| status                 = Active\n| functional status      = Cathedral\n| heritage designation   = [[Listed buildings in Sweden|Ecclesiastical monument]] in the buildings database of the [[Swedish National Heritage Board]].<ref name=raa>{{cite web |url= http://www.bebyggelseregistret.raa.se/bbr2/anlaggning/visaHistorik.raa?anlaggningId=21300000022524&page=historik&visaHistorik=true|title= Lund kn, DOMKYRKAN 1 LUNDS DOMKYRKA|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Bebyggelseregistret|publisher= [[Swedish National Heritage Board]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n| designated date        = \n| architect              = Donatus<br>[[Adam van D\u00fcren]]<br>[[Carl Georg Brunius]]<br>[[Helgo Zettervall]]\n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = \n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n\n| capacity               = \n| length                 = {{convert|85|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width                  = {{convert|30|m|ft}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}\n| width nave             = \n| height                 = {{convert|55|m|ft}} (to the top of the towers){{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}\n| diameter               = \n| other dimensions       = \n| floor area             = \n| dome quantity          = \n| dome height outer      = \n| dome height inner      = \n| dome dia outer         = \n| dome dia inner         = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           = \n| materials              = \n\n| diocese                = [[Diocese of Lund]]\n| bishop                 = [[Johan Tyrberg]]\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                = \n}}\n'''Lund Cathedral''' ({{lang-sv|Lunds domkyrka}}) is a [[cathedral]] of the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Church of Sweden]] in [[Lund]], [[Scania]], Sweden. It is the seat of the [[List of bishops of Lund|Bishop of Lund]] and the main church of the [[Diocese of Lund]]. It was built as the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] cathedral of the [[archiepiscopal see]] of all the [[Nordic countries]], dedicated to [[Lawrence of Rome|Saint Lawrence]]. It is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.\n\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the most powerful representative of [[Romanesque architecture]] in the Nordic countries\". At the time of its construction, Lund and the cathedral belonged to Denmark. The main altar was consecrated in 1145 and the cathedral was by that time largely finished; the western towers were built somewhat later. Its architecture show clear influences from contemporary north Italian architecture, conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]]. The earliest architect was named Donatus, though his precise role in the construction of the cathedral is difficult to determine. The new cathedral was richly decorated with stone sculpture, including two unusual statues in the crypt traditionally called \"[[Fin (troll)|The giant Finn and his wife]]\" about which a local legend has developed. The cathedral was severely damaged in a fire in 1234, and major restoration works were carried out in the early 16th century under the leadership of [[Adam van D\u00fcren]]. Following the [[Reformation in Denmark\u2013Norway and Holstein|Reformation]], the cathedral suffered from lost income and dilapidation. In 1658, the city of Lund and the cathedral became a part of Sweden following the [[Treaty of Roskilde]]. Lund Cathedral was the site of the ceremony founding [[Lund University]] in 1688. Repairs were made during the 18th century but in 1832 a complete restoration of the cathedral was recommended. Subsequently much of the cathedral was restored and rebuilt during most of the 19th century. The work was first led by [[Carl Georg Brunius]] and later by architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] and not entirely finished until 1893. The changes implemented during the 19th century were extensive; among other things, Zettervall had the entire western part, including the towers, demolished and rebuilt to his own designs.\n\nThe medieval cathedral contains several historic furnishings and works of art. Its main altarpiece was donated to the cathedral in 1398, and it also contains [[Gothic art|Gothic]] choir stalls, bronzes and an [[astronomical clock]] from the 15th century (although heavily restored in 1923). When it was built, Lund Cathedral was lavishly decorated with Romanesque stone sculptures. It also contains late medieval stone sculptures from the time of Adam van D\u00fcren's renovation. After the Reformation the cathedral was also equipped with a decorated [[pulpit]]. Of more recent date is the large [[mosaic]] in the [[apse]], by [[Joakim Skovgaard]], installed in 1927. Lund Cathedral has six [[church organ]]s, one of which is the largest in Sweden, and is also used as a concert venue.\n\n==Historical background==\nChristian missionaries from present-day Germany and England were active in the [[Christianization of Scandinavia|Christianisation of Denmark]], and Denmark eventually became part of the [[Prince-Archbishopric of Bremen|Archdiocese of Hamburg-Bremen]]. Lund was at the time part of Denmark. With the consolidation of Danish monarchy during the second half of the 11th century, and with a political crisis in continental Europe, there arose an opportunity for the Danish monarchs to bypass the German influence over church policy in Denmark.{{sfn|Ryd\u00e9n|1999|p=99\u2013100}} An [[episcopal see]] was created in Lund in 1060.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25}} At the same time, another see was created in [[Dalby, Lund Municipality|Dalby]], very close to Lund. However, when the first bishop of Lund ([[Henry of Lund]]) died, the erstwhile bishop of Dalby, [[Egino (Bishop of Dalby)|Egino]], was installed in Lund and Dalby abandoned as the seat of a bishop. At the same time, in 1103, Lund was proclaimed an archiepiscopal see overseeing all Nordic countries.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=25\u201329}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=4\u20135}}\n\nSome kind of rudimentary settlement probably existed at the site of Lund Cathedral at the end of the 10th and early 11th centuries, but no remains of buildings have been found there.{{sfn|Cinthio|1990|p=1}} Lund Cathedral is one of the oldest stone buildings still in use in Sweden.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=7}} During the [[Middle Ages]], the cathedral was surrounded by several buildings serving the diocese, of which only [[Liberiet]], which at one point served as a library, survives.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=69\u201371}}\n\n==History==\n===Foundation and construction===\n[[File:Lund domkyrka - crypt (by Pudelek).JPG|thumb|right|The [[crypt]], the oldest part of Lund Cathedral]]\n[[File:Lund Dom Chor.JPG|thumb|right|The [[apse]] is the most well-preserved part of the original exterior]]\nThe earliest written mention of a church in Lund dedicated to [[Saint Lawrence]] \u2014 the patron saint of Lund Cathedral during the Middle Ages \u2014 dates from 1085.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=37}} Slightly later sources mention both a new and an old church dedicated to Saint Lawrence.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=38}} During the 1940s, archaeological excavations in the cathedral uncovered the foundations of another church inside the present building. The exact age, shape and function of this predecessor to the cathedral has been a matter of some debate.{{sfn|Cinthio|1957|p=1\u201342}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=62\u201364}} Most scholars believe that construction of a church on the site of Lund Cathedral was begun sometime during the second half of the 11th century.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} Some time thereafter a new church was begun in almost the same place, but to a larger design in the form of the present cathedral. Parts of the earlier church may have been incorporated in the walls of the cathedral.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} The decision to abandon Dalby as a [[bishopric]] and make Lund the sole archbishopric in Scandinavia may have prompted the change of plans.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=40}}\n\nApart from the obscurity which thus surrounds the very beginning of the history of the cathedral, the construction of Lund Cathedral is probably among the most well documented among any [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque churches]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} Two contemporary accounts of the building of the cathedral, in the form of the [[illuminated manuscripts]] ''{{ill|Necrologium Lundense|sv}}'' and ''{{ill|Liber daticus vetustior|sv}}'', are still preserved in the library of [[Lund University]]. Both books contain notes, written in [[Latin language|Latin]], with dates of the progression of the construction. The oldest part of the cathedral is the large [[crypt]]. Its main [[altar]] was inaugurated on 30 June 1123, followed by the north (1126) and south (1131) side altars of the crypt. Only then did the cathedral begin to be used.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=28}} One of the main functions of the crypt appears to have been as a place where [[baptism]]s were conducted.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=4}} The main altar of the cathedral was dedicated to [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Saint Mary]] and Saint Lawrence in 1145, by the second archbishop of Lund, [[Eskil of Lund|Eskil]], in a ceremony attended by bishops from present-day Germany, Denmark and Sweden.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=29\u201330}} By then, the construction of the cathedral to more or less its present dimensions was complete.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2004|p=186\u2013187}}\n\nUnusually for that time, the architect of the cathedral is known by his name, Donatus.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=164}} The name appears in both the ''Necrologium Lundense'' (as \"Donatus architectus\") and the ''Liber daticus vetustior''. Donatus may have been responsible for the layout of the crypt and the cathedral above ground as far west as the current north and south portals of the cathedral, although it is difficult to draw any definitive conclusions about his precise role.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=30}}{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}} The same is true for his successor, possibly a builder named Ragnar.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=32}} The building erected during the time of Donatus and his successor show clear influences from Romanesque architecture in [[Lombardy]], conveyed via the [[Rhine Valley]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} Donatus himself appears to have been from, or at least educated in, Lombardy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=58}} [[Speyer Cathedral]] in western Germany is stylistically closely related to Lund Cathedral (especially the crypt), and it has been proposed that Donatus came to Lund from Speyer, where construction more or less ceased in 1106 following the death of [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry IV]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=59}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1923|p=148}} Similarities have also frequently been pointed out between Lund Cathedral and [[Mainz Cathedral]], and the design of the apse is similar to that of the [[Basilica of Saint Servatius]] in [[Maastricht]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} On a more general level, the origins of the style of Lund Cathedral can be found in [[Basilica of Sant'Ambrogio]] ([[Milan]]), [[Modena Cathedral]] and several churches in [[Pavia]], all in northern Italy.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Similar stylistic influences can be seen in other cathedrals in Denmark from the same time, for example in [[Ribe Cathedral]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64}}\n\nThe building of Lund Cathedral must have involved a large number of people and was a collective undertaking.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} Comparable but somewhat later workshops at [[Cologne Cathedral]] and [[Uppsala Cathedral]] employed a workforce of about 100 and 60 people, respectively.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The project was instrumental in establishing a workshop where local craftsmen could be educated, and thus disseminating artistic influences from continental Europe to Scandinavia. The stone sculptors {{ill|Carl stenm\u00e4stare|sv}}, {{ill|M\u00e5rten stenm\u00e4stare|sv}} and [[Majestatis]] were probably all Scandinavians who were educated at the construction site.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=62}} Many early Romanesque stone churches in the countryside, particularly in Scania but also in the rest of Sweden, show direct influences from Lund Cathedral, notably {{ill|V\u00e4 Church|sv|V\u00e4 kyrka}} (Scania).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=79\u201381}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=265\u2013281}} Other examples are e.g. {{ill|Lannaskede Old Church|sv|Lannaskede gamla kyrka}} ([[Sm\u00e5land]]), {{ill|Hogstad Church|sv|Hogstads kyrka}} ([[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]]) and [[Havdhem Church]] ([[Gotland]]).{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=90\u201392}}\n\n===Fire and repairs===\nThe plan and layout of the building consecrated in 1145 was similar to the one seen today. A noticeable difference was that the entire choir was separated from the nave by a wall and reserved for the clergy. The towers were also not built until a few decades later.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=52}} The intention was probably to provide the cathedral with [[vault (architecture)|vaults]], but instead a flat wooden ceiling was installed.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68\u201369}} The cathedral was adorned with [[Church murals in Sweden|wall paintings]] and almost certainly by [[Medieval stained glass in Sweden|stained glass windows]], but none of these remain.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} In 1234, the cathedral was heavily damaged by a large fire.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=78}} Large donations were made to the church in the following years, to allow for repairs.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=74}} Even so, the need for  repairs was continuous for the entire 13th century.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80}} Following the fire, the burnt-out ceiling was replaced by [[brick]] vaults.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}} Changes were also made to the layout of the westernmost part of the building.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76}} A conflict erupted between King [[Christopher I of Denmark]] and Archbishop [[Jakob Erlandsen]] in 1257 partially because the choir had been enlarged and the seats of the royal family moved, itself a testimony of the growing power of the Church.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=76\u201378}} Two [[chapel]]s were added to the cathedral during the 14th and 15th centuries; one located adjacent to the two westernmost [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] of the south aisle of the nave, and the other as a southern extension of the east transept.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=80\u201381}} [[Buttress]]es were also added piecemeal to the building during the 13th and 14th centuries, to stabilise the building which was under strain from the new, heavier vaults, the added chapels and the constant ringing of the 8.5 [[tonne]] [[church bell]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=86\u201387}}\n\n===Changes by Adam van D\u00fcren and later===\n[[File:Lunds domkyrka - KMB - 16001000533737.jpg|thumb|right|A drawing of the cathedral as it appeared in 1750]]\nThe German sculptor and builder [[Adam van D\u00fcren]] apparently worked intermittently at restoring and altering the cathedral between {{circa}} 1506 or 1507 and 1524.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=90\u201391}} Despite, and to some extent because of, the work that had been done during the preceding centuries since the great fire of 1234, the cathedral was in need of a thorough restoration.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=87}} Adam van D\u00fcren and his workshop made several changes and contributions. A new drainage system was installed in the crypt, and as part of that work a [[well]], which probably replaced an earlier well in the same location, was decorated with [[satire|satirical]] [[allegory|allegories]].{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=88\u201395}} The workshop of van D\u00fcren also created two new windows in the choir, built a large buttress to support the southern transept (before 1513), and rebuilt the [[gable]] of the northern transept (1524) as well as its vaults. New and considerably larger windows with [[Pointed arch (architecture)|pointed arches]] were installed in both the northern wall of the north transept and in the southern wall of the south transept.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=100}} The towers and western facade were also repaired in 1512\u201318 and again in 1527.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=91}} It has been argued that the cathedral may have collapsed, were it not for the work done by van D\u00fcren.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=104}}\n\nFollowing the Reformation in the 16th century, the diocese lost much of its revenues.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=126}} The building was still subjected to much stress, not least by the use of the large church bell, and suffered during the recurrent [[List of wars involving Denmark|wars between Denmark and Sweden]]; in 1658 Lund permanently became part of Sweden. Despite van D\u00fcren's repairs, the church was described as being \"very dilapidated\" in 1682.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128}} During the 18th century, the chapels of the church were used for funerals, but also as an improvised [[morgue]] where corpses were occasionally left for several years.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=130}} Attempts at repairs were made; among them the entire apse was dismantled and then re-erected.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=12}} Many of the repairs were however either temporary or outright detrimental to condition of the building. King [[Gustav III of Sweden]] visited the cathedral crypt in 1785 and expressed his displeasure at its state.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=132}} In 1812, the aforementioned chapels from the 14th and 15th centuries were demolished.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}}\n\n===Changes by Carl Georg Brunius and Helgo Zettervall===\n[[File:Demolition of the tower of Lund Cathedral.jpg|thumb|right|Demolition of the south tower of the cathedral during the time of [[Helgo Zettervall]]]]\nWhen the congregation wanted to build a new [[church organ]] in the early 19th century, architect {{ill|Axel Nystr\u00f6m|sv|Axel Nystr\u00f6m (1793\u20131868)}} was invited to examine the structure in 1832. Nystr\u00f6m recommended a complete renovation of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=134}} The chairman of the council in charge of administering the cathedral buildings, [[Carl Georg Brunius]], was called to execute the plans of Nystr\u00f6m, and he did so while at the same time making changes according to his own convictions. He also wrote the first systematic art history of the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} Brunius had the organ moved, the crypt repaired, installed a set of steps connecting the choir with the nave and improved the drainage system.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}} He also removed modern furnishings, re-built some of the buttresses and changed the stone of a large part of the facade.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121}} Brunius retired due to old age in 1859, but as there was still a substantial need for repairs, the young architect [[Helgo Zettervall]] was appointed to carry out the rest of the work in 1860.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013122}} A conflict between Brunius and Zettervall developed almost immediately, but Zettervall would keep working on restoring the cathedral until 1893 and ultimately managed to implement most of his ideas for the cathedral.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=121\u2013181}} A compromise in 1862 proposed that the Danish architect [[Ferdinand Meldahl]] would assume the main responsibility, and Zettervall would merely assist Meldahl. However, it soon became apparent that Zettervall would not accept a subordinate role and Meldahl himself showed little interest in the project.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=141}} In 1862, Zettervall traveled extensively through Germany and Italy to study stylistically related architecture, and also to visit the latest examples of building restoration so that he could draw upon that experience in his work at Lund.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=134\u2013141}} In 1863, he presented a first proposal for a complete restoration of the cathedral. Zettervall himself considered it a \"reasonable middle ground between reparation and reconstruction\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142}} The proposal would mean the removal of all buttresses, a new roof, completely rebuilt towers, and the removal of the large Gothic windows in the transepts. Zettervall also proposed to add an octagonal dome over the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]]. Far-reaching changes would also affect the interior. In the proposal Zettervall strove to reduce and refine the building volumes of the cathedral and create a unified composition of block-like elements.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=142\u2212152}}\n\nThe proposal by Zettervall was criticised, not least by Meldahl. Zettervall re-worked the proposal and put forward a revised, less far-reaching proposal in 1864, notably without the central dome.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=152}} This proposal was also rejected and the plan for a complete overhaul abandoned; however it was at the same time decided that Zettervall would continue working on repairing the cathedral and every year make what changes that were deemed necessary. In this way, Zettervall could piecemeal over the next decades to rebuild the cathedral largely in line with his design from 1864.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=135}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=158\u2013159}}\n\nBetween 1832 and 1893, the cathedral was radically transformed by the work of Brunius and Zettervall. All windows were replaced, several vaults and pillars were repaired or rebuilt, and both architects effected extensive changes to the transept. Just as he had suggested, Zettervall had all the buttresses removed and demolished the entire western part of the church, including the towers, and rebuilt them according to his own [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Neo-Romanesque]] designs.{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=13\u201314}}<ref name=byggnaden>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/byggnaden/|title= En kyrka i st\u00e4ndig f\u00f6r\u00e4ndring|trans-title= A constantly changing church|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn the 20th century, archaeological excavations were carried out in and around the cathedral. The building also underwent a major restoration in 1954\u20131963, led by architect {{ill|Eiler Gr\u00e6be|sv}}. During this time the decorative painting from the 19th century was removed.<ref name=byggnaden/> The large [[mosaic]] decorating the apse was installed in 1927, and designed by [[Joakim Skovgaard]].{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=14}} In 1990, the layout of the choir was changed and the altar placed in the crossing.<ref name=byggnaden/> [[Pope Francis]] visited the cathedral on 31 October 2016 to observe the 499th anniversary of the beginning of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Christina|title=Pope Francis, in Sweden, Urges Catholic-Lutheran Reconciliation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/01/world/europe/pope-francis-in-sweden-urges-catholic-lutheran-reconciliation.html|accessdate=1 November 2016|work=The New York Times|date=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and decoration==\nLund Cathedral has been called \"the most powerful representative of Romanesque architecture in the Nordic countries\".{{sfn|Sundn\u00e9r|1997|p=11}} It lies at some distance from any other buildings and dominates its surroundings.{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=181}} It consists of the two towers built by Zettervall, which flank the main entrance to the west. Behind them a [[nave]] with two [[aisle]]s open up to a [[transept]] that is somewhat higher than the nave. A short flight of stairs thus connect the nave with the [[choir (architecture)|choir]] as well as with the crypt under the choir. The choir ends in an apse. Inside, the bays of the cathedral are supported by [[groin vault]]s. The number of bays in the aisles are the double of that in the nave. The arches that separate the nave from the aisles are supported by piers and pillars of alternating width. The crypt has over forty shallow [[groin vault]]s supported by pillars with cushion-cap capitals. It is sparsely lit by low small windows.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=45}}\n\nSeen from outside, the different elements of the building are clearly discernible as independent volumes, \"as if they could be taken apart and put together again\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=181}} The apse of the cathedral is a \"forcefully articulated\" semi-circle of three storeys.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=68}} The apse is the most well-preserved part of the Romanesque building and has been described as \"the artistic high point of the exterior\".{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=124}} The southern portal of the nave is perhaps the oldest of the cathedral. Five decorated [[archivolt]]s supported by small columns with variously decorated [[capital (architecture)|capitals]], frame a [[tympanon]] depicting the [[Lamb of God]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=70\u201371}} The northern portal is slightly later and more richly decorated. Its tympanon depicts [[Samson]] wrestling with the lion.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=72\u201373}} Two bronze doors built by {{ill|Carl Johan Dyfverman|sv|Carl Johan Dyfverman (konstn\u00e4r)}} serve as the main entrance in the centre of the west facade. They have 24 reliefs with subjects from the Bible, particularly the Old Testament. Above the doorway, the tympanon depicts [[Christ]], [[Canute IV of Denmark]] and Saint Lawrence.<ref name=byggnaden/> The cathedral has two [[sacristy|sacristies]].{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}} The building material of the cathedral is mostly [[sandstone]] quarried in the area around [[H\u00f6\u00f6r]]. The main walls are constructed as shells of sandstone filled with [[fieldstone]] mixed with [[lime mortar]]. The thickness of the walls is around {{convert|2 to 3|m|ft}}.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}{{sfn|Bodin|2017|p=126\u2013127}} \n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Overview of Lund Cathedral\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Lunds domkyrka. Plan.png|Plan\nFile:Lunds domkyrka\u2013flygbild 06 september 2014.jpg|Aerial view from the south east\nFile:Lund Cathedral 2017-08-17 4.jpg|View from the entrance towards east\nFile:Lund cathedral interior 2015-03-30-4746.jpg|View from the altar towards west\n</gallery>\n\n===Sculptures===\n[[File:Finn the Giant, Lund Cathedral crypt 2017-08-17 1.jpg|thumb|right|\"[[Fin (troll)|The giant Finn and his wife]]\" in the crypt, probably a depiction of the biblical hero [[Samson]]]]\nWhen it comes to stone sculpture, Lund Cathedral was the most lavishly decorated Romanesque building to be built in the Nordic countries according to art historian {{ill|Jan Svanberg|sv}}.{{sfn|Svanberg|1995|p=152}} Perhaps the most well-known and striking of these are the sculptures of two figures traditionally called \"[[Fin (troll)|The giant Finn and his wife]]\" in the crypt.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} According to a local legend, the giant helped build the cathedral, and when he was not payed for his services he tried to destroy it by shaking the pillars, but was petrified.<ref name=finn>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/jatten-finn/|title= J\u00e4tten Finn vakar \u00f6ver kryptan|trans-title= The giant Finn watches over the crypt|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The larger of the two figures is embracing a column, while the smaller is attached to another column with a rope. These sculptures have probably been the subject of more attempts at an explanation than any other medieval artworks in Sweden, according to art historian Mereth Lindgren.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}} Most scholars today believe the larger sculpture depicts [[Samson]], but what the smaller figure is supposed to represent is not known. The sculptures date from the construction of the crypt but have been treated poorly, especially during the 18th century, and lost much of their original detailing.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=77}}\n\nThe fluted columns also found in the crypt are similar in style to [[Norman architecture|English Norman architecture]] and may indicate that the very first artistic influences came from the area bordering the [[English Channel]].{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=64\u201365}} Apart from these columns however, the rich stone ornamentation is clearly [[wikt:Lombardic|Lombardic]] in style, meaning related to north Italian art of the period.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=66}} Among these is a [[baldachin]] now immured in the east wall of the north transept which may have been part of the original western facade; Its columns have [[Corinthian order|Corinthian capitals]] and support a richly decorated archivolt on which traces of original paint survives. Opposite, in the south wall, is a smaller baldachin where the columns themselves are sculpted angels (one with [[feather tights]]) standing on lions. Similar sculptures exist in [[Como]] and Modena in northern Italy.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=74\u201375}} In addition, the capitals of the columns in the church are all of high [[wikt:artisanal|artisanal]] quality, and can be broadly divided into two groups displaying either [[Classical architecture|Classical]] or [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine]] influences.{{sfn|Lindgren|1995|p=75}} Apart from its rich Romanesque decoration, Lund Cathedral also contains several late medieval sculptures made by Adam van D\u00fcren, as mentioned above. Several of these are of animals and contain inscriptions in [[Low German]]. A relief in the south transept displaying the [[Woman of the Apocalypse]] flanked by Saint Lawrence and Saint Canute is similar to the portal relief van D\u00fcren made a couple of years earlier at [[Glimmingehus]].{{sfn|Svanberg|1996|p=196\u2013197}}\n\n===Altarpiece===\nThe medieval main [[altarpiece]] was donated to the cathedral in 1398 by [[Ide Pedersdatter Falk]].<ref name=kor>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/hogkoret/|title= Gyllene mosaik och korstolar fr\u00e5n 1300-talet|trans-title= Golden mosaics and choir stalls from the 14th century|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The altarpiece is stylistically similar to a group of altarpieces from northern Germany. Its central panel depicts the [[Coronation of the Virgin]], surrounded by two rows of 40 saints, 26 of which are original. Twelve figures have been taken from other medieval altarpieces, while two of the added figures are from the 17th century. The altarpiece is {{convert|7.6|m|ft}} wide but is missing an original pair of wings.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=20\u201323}}{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=112\u2013113}}\n\n===Choir stalls===\n[[File:Lunds Domkyrka korstolar h\u00f6ger om koret.JPG|thumb|right|The right side of the choir, showing parts of the choir stalls (right) and the main altarpiece (left)]]\nThe choir contains two rows of medieval choir stalls containing in total 78 seats. The wooden stalls date from the end of the 14th century, probably commissioned by archbishop Nils J\u00f6nson some time between 1361 and 1379. Clearly made by several different wood carvers, they are approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall without their gables and decorated with carved details. These are biblical scenes from both the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]], but the stalls also contain [[misericord]]s portraying animals and other small details. Their style is [[Gothic art|High Gothic]] and they are stylistically linked with contemporary art from the Rhine Valley. They are among the largest wooden Gothic sculptures to survive in the Nordic countries, and have been described as being of internationally high quality.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}} The choir stalls in Lund Cathedral also lent stylistic inspiration to the choir stalls in [[Roskilde Cathedral]] and [[St. Bendt's Church, Ringsted]].{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=24\u201332}}{{sfn|Dun\u00e9r|1984|p=1\u20139}}\n\nSlightly older than the choir stalls is a [[Cathedra|bishop's throne]] which survives in a damaged state and is placed in the south transept. It is somewhat similar in construction to the choir stalls but stylistically different and more closely related to contemporary art from north Germany.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=32\u201335}} Currently placed next to the bishop's chair is also a Gothic [[Church tabernacle|tabernacle]] in the form of a {{convert|5|m|ft}} tall, decorated wooden pillar. It contains two cabinets surmounted by a statuette of a female saint and crowned by a hexagonal spire. The tabernacle was repaired by Brunius in the 19th century. The saint may  be {{ill|Ida von Toggenburg|de}}.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=36\u201337}}\n\n===Astronomical clock===\n{{Main|Horologium mirabile Lundense}}\n[[File:Lunds astronomiska ur-2.jpg|thumb|right|The [[astronomical clock]]]]\nThe [[astronomical clock]] of Lund Cathedral, presently located at the west end of the north aisle, dates from the late Middle Ages and was installed in Lund Cathedral {{circa}} 1425. In 1837, it was dismantled. It was restored at the initiative of architect {{ill|Theodor W\u00e5hlin|sv}} and the Danish clock-maker Julius Bertram Larsen and re-inaugurated in 1923. The upper part, which is original, is the clock, while the lower part, a reconstruction, is a calendar. Twice every day the two knights on the top clash their swords. The clock then plays the tune ''[[In dulci jubilo]]'' and a procession of figures parades across the face of the clock.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=125\u2013126}} Three astronomical clocks of similar design are preserved in Europe. The clock in Lund was repaired 2009\u20132010.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}<ref name=svt>{{cite web |url= https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/skane/lund-uret-i-domkyrkan-slutar-sla|title= Lund \u2013 Uret i domkyrkan slutar sl\u00e5|trans-title= The clock in  the cathedral ceases to strike|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 12 October 2009|website= |publisher= [[Sveriges television]]|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref><ref name=uret>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/uret/|title= Det underbara uret i Lund|trans-title= The astonishing clock in Lund|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nA decorated conventional clock from 1623 is immured on the opposite side of the nave, in the west wall of the south aisle.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=126}}\n\n===Bronzes===\nThe cathedral also owns three High Gothic [[bronze]] columns carrying statuettes and a seven-branched candelabrum from the end of the Middle Ages. Two of the bronze columns are crowned by angels, and the third one by a statuette of Saint Lawrence, holding a gridiron, the symbol of his martyrdom. It probably dates from the middle of the 14th century, while the two angel-bearing columns may be somewhat later. Saint Lawrence's column is approximately {{convert|3|m|ft}} tall (and the saint {{convert|70|cm|inch}}), while the columns with angels are slightly smaller.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114}} The three columns were probably made in [[L\u00fcbeck]] or [[Hamburg]]. Presently located in the south transept is also the {{convert|3.5|m|ft}} tall seven-branched candelabrum or candle holder from the late 15th century, manufactured by Harmen Bonstede in Hamburg.<ref name=stake>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/rundtur/sjuarmade-ljusstakens-kapell/|title= V\u00e5r tids martyrer och den sjuarmade ljusstaken|trans-title= The martyrs of our time and the seven-branched candelabrum|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> It was supplied to the cathedral in a dismantled state, and traces of its assembly instruction are still discernible on the candelabrum. Similar candelabra were installed in a number of Scandinavian cathedrals at approximately the same time; although the one in Lund is larger than those in the cathedrals of [[Aarhus Cathedral|Aarhus]], Ribe, [[Viborg Cathedral|Viborg]] and [[Storkyrkan|Stockholm]].<ref name=stake/>{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=114\u2013116}}\n\n===Pulpit===\nThe current [[pulpit]] was commissioned at the end of the 16th century and is marked with the date 1592. The artist was [[Johannes Ganssog]] from [[Frankfurt an der Oder]] in present-day Germany. It is attached with unusual technical skill to one of the pillars of the nave, and it is entered through a stair cut inside the pillar. The building material is sandstone, black [[limestone]] and black and white [[marble]], and it is partially painted and [[gilding|gilded]]. Reliefs of [[alabaster]] on the side show scenes from the New Testament.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=60\u201364}}{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}\n\n===Graves and funerary monuments===\n[[File:Herman af Slesvig (gravsten).JPG|thumb|right|The grave of Hermann, [[List of the bishops of Schleswig|bishop of Schleswig]], 12th century, the oldest grave in the crypt]]\nThe crypt contains the oldest grave in the cathedral, the grave of Hermann, [[List of the bishops of Schleswig|bishop of Schleswig]], who played an important role as an emissary of archbishop Eskil of Lund during the negotiations to establish Lund as an independent archdiocese. The simple Romanesque [[sarcophagus]], which has an inscription in Latin and a depiction of the bishop, is located in the apse of the crypt. It dates from the middle of the 12th century.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=48}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=46}} The crypt also contains the much larger grave monument of the last archbishop, {{ill|Birger Gunnersen|sv}}, which is centrally placed in the crypt. It is of a kind which is not unusual in continental Europe but very unusual in the Nordic countries: a large stone sarcophagus decorated on all sides with sculptures in high relief and with a full-scale depiction of the bishop in full dress on the lid. It was made by Adam van D\u00fcren in 1512.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=94}}{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=48\u201349}} The cathedral's largest grave monument is that of bishop [[Hans Brostorp]], who died in 1497 and who during his lifetime inaugurated the [[University of Copenhagen]]. The monument is made of limestone from [[Gotland]] and decorated in low relief.{{sfn|Wrangel|1915|p=47}}\n\nThe nave and the aisles contain several memorial plaques and [[epitaph]]s. Several commemorate bishops, such as {{ill|Johan Engestr\u00f6m|sv}} (1699\u20131777) and {{ill|Nils Hessl\u00e9n|sv}} (1728\u20131811). Many others were made for professors at Lund University, e.g. {{ill|Eberhard Rosenblad|sv}} (1714\u20131796) and {{ill|Erasmus Sack|sv}} (1633\u20131697). The oldest epitaph of the cathedral commemorates the owner of [[Krageholm Castle]] {{ill|Lave Brahe|sv}} (1500\u20131567) and his wife [[G\u00f6rvel Fadersdotter (Sparre)]] (1509 or 1517 \u2013 1605).{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=122\u2013125}}\n\n===Baptismal font===\nThe [[baptismal font]] of the cathedral is a sparsely decorated Early Gothic font made of reddish grey limestone.{{sfn|Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|2014|p=187}}\n\n==Flora==\n[[File:Flickr - Sigfrid Lundberg - Wall-rue, Asplenium ruta-muraria.jpg|thumb|right|[[Asplenium ruta-muraria|Wall-rue]] growing on the [[apse]]]]\nSeveral surveys and descriptions of the [[flora]] of the cathedral, like the plants that grow on its walls, have been made. The first to describe the flora of the cathedral was [[Daniel Rolander]], one of the [[apostles of Linnaeus]], who made a list of the [[vascular plant]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]] he found growing on the building in 1771.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} It was rediscovered in the 20th century and published in 1931. [[Elias Magnus Fries]] also made observations about the flora of the cathedral during the first half of the 19th century. More systematic surveys of the flora of the building have been published in 1922 and in 1993 (the latter only encompassing lichen).{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=25}} Of the species observed growing on the cathedral, the minute [[fern]] [[Asplenium ruta-muraria|wall-rue]] was mentioned as early as 1756 by {{ill|Anders Tidstr\u00f6m|sv}} and is perhaps the most conspicuous member of the cathedral flora.{{sfn|Gertz|1923|p=458}} When the lichen flora was surveyed in 1993, 15 species were discovered. One of these, ''[[Lecanora perpruinosa]]'', had not been observed in the province of Scania before.{{sfn|Johansson|1993|p=26}}\n\n==Relationship with Lund University==\nThe founding of [[Lund University]] was acknowledged in a ceremony in the cathedral in 1668.<ref name=nyckeltal>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/nyckelartal/|title= Ett p\u00e4rlband av h\u00e4ndelser|trans-title= A string of events|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> Following the Reformation, the choir was used for a long time as a classroom, first by [[Lund Cathedral School]] and later by the university. The university also used the choir to store its [[library]] for some time.{{sfn|Rydbeck|1946|p=128\u2013129}} The cathedral is still the place for the ceremony of the [[wikt:conferment|conferment]] of new doctor's degrees at the university.<ref name=universitet>{{cite web |url= https://www.lu.se/om-universitetet/akademiska-hogtider/doktorspromotionen/promotionsdagen|title= Promotionsdagen|trans-title= The day of conferment of the doctor's degree|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= [[Lund University]]|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe cathedral has five [[choir (music)|choirs]] for adults and two choirs for children.<ref name=korer>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/musik-kultur/korer-2/|title= K\u00f6rer|trans-title= Choirs|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 20 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> The cathedral is also frequently used for concerts.<ref name=konserter>{{cite web |url=https://lundsdomkyrka.se/musik-kultur/konserter/|title= Konserter varje vecka|trans-title= Concerts every week|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 23 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThere are currently six church organs in Lund Cathedral, including the largest church organ in Sweden. The gallery organ was built between 1932 and 1934 by the Danish company [[Marcussen & S\u00f8n]] and renovated by the same company in 1992. It has 102 stops distributed between four manuals and a pedalboard. There are 7,074 pipes in total. The smallest organ is inside the astronomical clock, where it plays ''In dulci jubilo''.<ref name=orglar>{{cite web |url= https://lundsdomkyrka.se/fordjupning/orglar/|title= Sex orglar i Domkyrkan|trans-title= Six organs in the cathedral|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= Lund Cathedral (official site)|publisher= Church of Sweden|access-date= 19 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last= Bodin|first= Anders|date= 2017|title= Helgo Zettervalls arkitektur: kyrkor|volume=II|trans-title= The architecture of Helgo Zettervall: churches|url= http://kth.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1094819/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Carlssons bokf\u00f6rlag|isbn=9789173317856}}\n*{{cite book |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1957|title= Lunds domkyrka under romansk tid|trans-title= Lund Cathedral during the Romanesque era|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/21557081/Diss_Erik_Cinthio.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Cinthio|first= Erik|date= 1990|title= Lunds domkyrkas f\u00f6rhistoria. S:t Laurentiuspatrociniet och Knut den Heliges kyrka \u00e4n en g\u00e5ng|trans-title= The pre-history of Lund Cathedral. The patronage of St. Lawrence and the church of Canute the Holy once more|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1990-2_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 2|issue= |pages= 1\u201313|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Dun\u00e9r|first= Uno|date= 1984|title= Gideon och ullen|trans-title= Gideon and the wool|url= https://www.tidskriftenale.nu/pdfale/ALE-1984-3_v02.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Ale. Historisk tidskrift f\u00f6r Sk\u00e5ne, Halland och Blekinge|volume= 3|issue= |pages= 1\u201310|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Gertz|first= Otto|date= 1923|title= Vegetationen \u00e5 ruinerna av Alvastra klosterkyrka|trans-title= The vegetation on the ruins of Alvastra monastery church|url= |language= Swedish|journal= Botaniska notiser|volume= |issue= |pages= 457\u2013463|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite journal |last= Johansson|first= Per|date= 1993|title= Lavfloran p\u00e5 Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The lichen flora of Lund Cathedral|url= http://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1203014/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|journal= Svensk Botanisk Tidskrift|volume= |issue= 87|pages= 25\u201330|doi= |access-date=}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Karlsson|editor1-first=Lennart|last= Lindgren|first= Mereth|date= 1995|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den romanska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenarkitekturen|trans-chapter=The stone architecture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0}}\n*{{cite book |last= Rydbeck|first= Otto|date= 1915|title= Bidrag till Lunds domkyrkas byggnadshistoria|trans-title= Contributions to the building history of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694254|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= Newman|editor1-first= Ernst|last= Rydbeck|first= Otto|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrkas historia 1145\u20131945|trans-title= History of Lund Cathedral 1145\u20131945|chapter= Lunds domkyrka, byggnadens och dess inventariers historia enligt de nyaste forskningsresultaten|trans-chapter= Lund Cathedral, the history of the building and its furnishings according to the latest research|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/8073961|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Svenska kyrkans diakonistyrelses bokf\u00f6rlag}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|editor1-first= Claes|last= Ryd\u00e9n|first= Thomas|date= 1998|title= Metropolis Daniae: ett stycke Europa|trans-title= Metropolis Daniae: a piece of Europe|chapter= Lunds domkyrka, det universella rummet|trans-chapter= Lund Cathedral, the universal space|url= https://portal.research.lu.se/portal/files/63935286/Ryden_LundsDomkyrkaUniversellaRummet.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Lund University|issn=0454-5915}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last= L\u00f6fvendahl|editor1-first= Runo|editor2-last= Sundn\u00e9r|editor2-first= Barbro|last= Sundn\u00e9r|first= Barbro|date= 1997|title= Lunds domkyrka: stenmaterial och skadebild|trans-title= Lund Cathedral: stone material and damages|chapter= Byggnadshistoria|trans-chapter= Building history|url= http://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:1289650/FULLTEXT01.pdf|language= Swedish|location= Stockholm|publisher= Riksantikvarie\u00e4mbetet ([[Swedish National Heritage Board]])|isbn=91-7209-006-5}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Karlsson|editor1-first=Lennart|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1995|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den romanska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Romanesque art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Augustsson|editor1-first=Jan-Erik|last= Svanberg|first= Jan|date= 1996|title=Signums svenska konsthistoria. Den gotiska konsten|trans-title= Signum's history of Swedish art. Gothic art|chapter=Stenskulpturen|trans-chapter=The stone sculpture|url= |language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Signum|pages=299\u2013335|isbn=91-87896-23-0}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1915|title= Konstverk i Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= Art in Lund Cathedral|url= https://archive.org/details/konstverkilundsd00wran/mode/2up|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wrangel|first= Ewert|date= 1923|title= Lunds domkyrkas konsthistoria: f\u00f6rbindelser och stilfr\u00e4nder|trans-title= The art history of Lund Cathedral: connections and stylistic equals|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/416081|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wahl\u00f6\u00f6|first= Claes|date= 2014|title= Sk\u00e5nes kyrkor 1050-1949|trans-title= The churches of Sk\u00e5ne 1050\u20131949|language=Swedish|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/18066221|location= K\u00e4vlinge|publisher= Domus Propria|isbn= 978-91-637-5874-4}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last= Brunius|first= Carl Georg|date= 1836|title= Nordens \u00e4ldsta metropolitankyrka, eller, historisk och arkitektonisk beskrifning \u00f6fver Lunds domkyrka|trans-title= The oldest metropolitan church in the Nordic countries, or, historic and architectonic description of Lund Cathedral|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/1694639|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= Berling}}\n*{{cite book |last= Gierow|first= Krister|date= 1946|title= Lunds domkyrka i litteraturen: bibliografisk f\u00f6rteckning|trans-title= Lund Cathedral in literature: a bibliography|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= C. W. K. Gleerup|url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/1186054}}\n*{{cite book |last= Zettervall|first= Helgo|date= 1916|title= Helgo Zettervall om Lunds domkyrka: en byggnadsbeskrivning i brev|trans-title= Helgo Zettervall on Lund Cathedral: description of a building in letters|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/10258926|language= Swedish|location= Lund|publisher= }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Lunds domkyrka|Lund Cathedral}}\n* [https://lundsdomkyrka.se/ Official website of the cathedral]\n* [http://www.alvin-portal.org/alvin/view.jsf?pid=alvin-record%3A14714&dswid=3243 Digitised copy of the 