"\n|-\n! Province\n! Winners\n! Runners-up\n! % Wins per final\n! Winning teams\n! Runners-up\n|-\n|align=center| [[Munster Senior Hurling Championship|Munster]]\n|align=center| 73\n|align=center| 45\n|align=center| 61%\n| [[Cork GAA|Cork]] (30), [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] (28), [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] (8), [[Clare GAA|Clare]] (4), [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] (2), [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] (1)\n| [[Cork GAA|Cork]] (19), [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] (13), [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] (9), [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] (5), [[Clare GAA|Clare]] (3)\n|-\n|align=center| [[Leinster Senior Hurling Championship|Leinster]]\n|align=center| 53\n|align=center| 57\n|align=center| 49%\n| [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] (36), [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] (6), [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] (6), [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] (4), [[Laois GAA|Laois]] (1)\n| [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] (27), [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] (15), [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] (11), [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] (3), [[Laois GAA|Laois]] (2)\n|-\n|align=center| [[Connacht Senior Hurling Championship|Connacht]]\n|align=center| 5\n|align=center| 20\n|align=center| 20%\n| [[Galway GAA|Galway]] (5)\n| [[Galway GAA|Galway]] (20)\n|-\n|align=center| [[Britain GAA|Britain]]\n|align=center| 1\n|align=center| 3\n|align=center| 25%\n| [[London GAA|London]] (1)\n| [[London GAA|London]] (3)\n|-\n|align=center| [[Ulster Senior Hurling Championship|Ulster]]\n|align=center| 0\n|align=center| 2\n|align=center| 0%\n| \n| [[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] (2)\n|}\n\n==Counties==\n\n===By decade===\nThe most successful team of each decade, judged by number of All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship titles, is as follows:\n\n* 1890s: 4 each for [[Cork GAA|Cork]] (1890, 92, 93, 94) and [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] (1895, 96, 98, 99)\n* 1900s: 4 for [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] (1904, 05, 07, 09)\n* 1910s: 3 for Kilkenny (1911, 12, 13)\n* 1920s: 3 each for [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] (1920, 24, 27) and Cork (1926, 28, 29)\n* 1930s: 4 for Kilkenny (1932, 33, 35, 39)\n* 1940s: 5 for Cork (1941, 42, 43, 44, 46)\n* 1950s: 3 each for Tipperary (1950, 51, 58) and Cork (1952, 53, 54)\n* 1960s: 4 for Tipperary (1961, 62, 64, 65)\n* 1970s: 4 each for Cork (1970, 76, 77, 78) and Kilkenny (1972, 74, 75, 79)\n* 1980s: 3 for [[Galway GAA|Galway]] (1980, 87, 88)\n* 1990s: 2 each for Cork (1990, 99); Kilkenny (1992, 93); [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] (1994, 98) and [[Clare GAA|Clare]] (1995, 97)\n* 2000s: 7 for Kilkenny (2000, 02, 03, 06, 07, 08, 09)\n* 2010s: 4 for Kilkenny (2011, 12, 14, 15)\n\n===By semi-final appearances===\n\n;''As of 15 July 2018''\n\n{| clas=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!width=20%|Team\n! No. of Appearances\n!------ First and Latest Semi-finals\n|-\n|[[Galway GAA|Galway]]||align=center|87||align=center|1887 - 2018 \n|-\n|[[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]]||align=center|55||align=center|1887 - 2019\n|-\n|[[Cork GAA|Cork]]||align=center|41||align=center|1901 - 2018 \n|-\n|[[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]]||align=center|37||align=center|1887 - 2019\n|-\n|[[Antrim GAA|Antrim]]||align=center|29||align=center|1900 - 1996 \n|-\n|[[Limerick GAA|Limerick]]||align=center|18||align=center|1911 - 2019\n|-\n|[[Wexford GAA|Wexford]]||align=center|16||align=center|1887 - 2019 \n|-\n|[[Waterford GAA|Waterford]]||align=center|15||align=center|1938 - 2017 \n|-\n|[[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]||align=center|14||align=center|1902 - 2013 \n|-\n|[[Clare GAA|Clare]]||align=center|12||align=center|1914 - 2018 \n|-\n|[[Offaly GAA|Offaly]]||align=center|11||align=center|1980 - 2000\n|-\n|[[London GAA|London]]||align=center|6||align=center|1906 - 1973 \n|-\n|[[Derry GAA|Derry]]||align=center|2||align=center|1902 - 1909 \n|-\n|[[Laois GAA|Laois]]||align=center|2||align=center|1915 - 1949\n|-\n|[[Down GAA|Down]]||align=center|2||align=center|1992 - 1995 \n|-\n|[[Cavan GAA|Cavan]]||align=center|1||align=center|1908\n|-\n|[[Mayo GAA|Mayo]]||align=center|1||align=center|1909\n|-\n|[[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]]||align=center|1||align=center|1913\n|-\n|[[Monaghan GAA|Monaghan]]||align=center|1||align=center|1915\n|-\n|[[Donegal GAA|Donegal]]||align=center|1||align=center|1923 \n|-\n|[[Lancashire GAA|Lancashire]]||align=center|1||align=center|1913  \n|-\n|[[Scotland GAA|Glasgow]]||align=center|1||align=center|1910  \n|-\n|[[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]||align=center|0||align=center|\n|-\n|[[Carlow GAA|Carlow]]||align=center|0||align=center|\n|-\n|[[Meath GAA|Meath]]||align=center|0||align=center|\n|-\n|[[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]]||align=center|0||align=center|\n|}\n\n===Other records===\n\n====Beaten sides====\nBetween 1887 and 1996 the championship was played on a straight knock out format whereby the All-Ireland champions were the only undefeated team of the competition.  The introduction of the qualifier system in 1997 has resulted in five 'back-door' All-Ireland champions:\n* [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] ([[1998 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1998]]) were beaten by [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] in the Leinster final.\n* [[Cork GAA|Cork]] ([[2004 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2004]]) were beaten by [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] in the Munster final.\n* [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] ([[2010 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2010]]) were beaten by [[Cork GAA|Cork]] in the first round of the Munster championship.\n*[[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] ([[2012 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2012]]) were beaten by [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in the Leinster final.\n* [[Clare GAA|Clare]] ([[2013 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2013]]) were beaten by [[Cork GAA|Cork]] in the Munster semi final.\n\nOn a number of occasions teams have been defeated twice but have remained in the championship:\n* [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] ([[2005 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2005]]) were beaten by [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] and [[Galway GAA|Galway]] but still qualified for the All-Ireland quarter-final.\n* [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] ([[2005 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2005]]) were beaten by [[Cork GAA|Cork]] and [[Clare GAA|Clare]] but still qualified for the All-Ireland quarter-final.\n* [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] ([[2006 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2006]]) were beaten by [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] and [[Clare GAA|Clare]] but still qualified for the All-Ireland quarter-final.\n* [[Cork GAA|Cork]] ([[2007 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2007]]) were beaten by [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] and [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] but still qualified for the All-Ireland quarter-final.\n\n====Final success rate====\nOnly one county has appeared in the final once, being victorious on that occasion:\n*[[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] ([[1891 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1891]])\n\n====Historic success rate====\nWhen a county won its first All Ireland before losing a final at a later time\n*[[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] (1887\u20131909)\n\nOn the opposite end of the scale, only one county has appeared in the final more than once, losing on each occasion:\n*[[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] ([[1943 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1943]], [[1989 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1989]])\n\n====Winning other trophies====\nAlthough not an officially recognised achievement, a number of teams have achieved the distinction of winning the All-Ireland championship, their provincial championship and the [[National Hurling League]]:\n* [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] in 1933, 1982, 1983, 2002, 2003, 2006, 2009 and 2014.\n* [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] in 1949, 1950, 1961, 1964, 1965, 1988 and 2001.\n* [[Cork GAA|Cork]] in 1926, 1941 and 1953.\n* [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] in 1934 and 1936\n* [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in 1987 and 2017.\n* [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] in 1956.\n\n====Biggest wins====\n* The most one sided All-Ireland finals:\n** '''34 points''' \u2013 [[1896 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1896]]: [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] 8-14 \u2013 0-4 [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n** '''29 points''' \u2013 [[1894 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1894]]: [[Cork GAA|Cork]] 5-20 \u2013 2-0 [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n** '''27 points''' \u2013 [[1943 All-Ireland Sen