rim GAA|Antrim]] 10-04 \u2013 2-00 [[Down GAA|Down]]\n** '''27 points''' \u2013 [[1935 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1935]]: [[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] 7-09 \u2013 0-03 [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]]\n** '''26 points''' \u2013 [[2007 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|2007]]: [[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] 2-24 \u2013 0-04 [[Down GAA|Down]]\n* The most one sided Connaught finals:\n** '''41 points''' \u2013 [[1922 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1922]]: [[Galway GAA|Galway]] 12-08 \u2013 1-00 [[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]]\n** '''38 points''' \u2013 [[1997 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1997]]: [[Galway GAA|Galway]] 6-24 \u2013 0-05 [[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]]\n** '''24 points''' \u2013 [[1999 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1999]]: [[Galway GAA|Galway]] 4-26 \u2013 2-08 [[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]]\n** '''21 points''' \u2013 [[1905 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1905]]: [[Galway GAA|Galway]] 3-15 \u2013 1-00 [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]]\n** '''18 points''' \u2013 [[1909 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|1909]]: [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]] 10-01 \u2013 4-01 [[Galway GAA|Galway]]\n\n====Successful defending====\nOnly 5 teams of the 13 who have won the All-Ireland championship have ever successfully defended the title. These are:\n\n* [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] on 13 attempts out of 36 (1905, 1912, 1913, 1933, 1975, 1983, 1993, 2003, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2012, 2015)\n* [[Cork GAA|Cork]] on 12 attempts out of 30 (1893, 1894, 1903, 1929, 1942, 1943, 1944, 1953, 1954, 1977, 1978, 2005)\n* [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] on 7 attempts out of 27 (1896, 1899, 1900, 1950, 1951, 1962, 1965)\n* [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] on 1 attempt out of 6 (1956)\n* [[Galway GAA|Galway]] on 1 attempt out of 4 (1988)\n\n====Gaps====\n\n* Longest gaps between successive All-Ireland titles: \n** '''81 years''': [[Clare GAA|Clare]] (1914\u20131995)\n** '''57 years''': [[Galway GAA|Galway]] (1923\u20131980)\n** '''45 years''': [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] (1910\u20131955) \n** '''45 years''': [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] (1973\u20132018)\n** '''33 years''': [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] (1940\u20131973)\n** '''29 years''': [[Galway GAA|Galway]] (1988\u20132017)\n** '''28 years''': [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] (1889\u20131917)\n** '''28 years''': [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] (1968\u20131996)\n** '''21 years''': [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] (1897\u20131918)\n** '''18 years''': [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] (1971\u20131989)\n** '''16 years''': [[Cork GAA| Cork]] (1903-1919)\n** '''14 years''': [[Cork GAA|Cork]] (2005-Present)\n\n* Longest gaps between successive All-Ireland final appearances: \n** '''63 years''': [[Clare GAA|Clare]] (1932\u20131995)\n** '''46 years''': [[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] (1943\u20131989)\n** '''45 years''': [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] (1963\u20132008)\n** '''34 years''': [[Laois GAA|Laois]] (1915\u20131949)\n** '''33 years''': [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] (1918\u20131951)\n** '''33 years''': [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] (1940\u20131973)\n\n====Provinces====\n*Only on four occasions has the All-Ireland final involved two teams from the same province:\n**[[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] vs [[Clare GAA|Clare]] ([[1997 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1997]])\n**[[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] vs [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] ([[1998 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1998]])\n**[[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] vs [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] ([[2000 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2000]])\n**[[Cork GAA|Cork]] vs [[Clare GAA|Clare]] ([[2013 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2013]])\n*The province providing the highest number of different winning teams is [[Munster Senior Hurling Championship|Munster]], with six: [[Clare GAA|Clare]], [[Cork GAA|Cork]], [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]], [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]], [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] and [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]].\n\n====Longest undefeated run====\nThe record for the longest unbeaten run stands at 21 games held by [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]]. It began with a 1-23 to 1-9 win against [[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]] in their opening game of the [[2006 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2006 championship]] and finished with a 3-22 to 0-19 win against [[Cork GAA|Cork]] in the All-Ireland semi-final of the [[2010 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|2010 championship]]. The 21-game unbeaten streak, which included no drawn game, ended with a 4-17 to 1-18 loss to [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] in the [[2010 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|2010 All-Ireland final]].\n\nThis broke the previous record of 16 consecutive games unbeaten by [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]], which began in May 1949 with a victory in the opening round of the championship, and ended with a seventeen-point defeat of [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] in the Munster semi-final of the [[1952 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship|1952 championship]]. The 16-game unbeaten streak, which included 15 wins and one draw, ended with a 1-11 to 2-6 loss to [[Cork GAA|Cork]] in the subsequent Munster final.\n\n==Players==\n\n===All-time top scorers===\n\n;''As of 18 August 2019''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''All-time top scorers in the All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship'''\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Scores!!Tally!!Games!!Era!!Average\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=center|1\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Henry Shefflin]]\n|[[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]]\n|28-485\n|569\n|71 games\n|1999-2014\n|8.0\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=center|2\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''[[Joe Canning]]'''\n|[[Galway GAA|Galway]]\n|27-425\n|506\n|56 games\n|2008\u2013present\n|9.03\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=center|3\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''[[Patrick Horgan]]'''\n|[[Cork GAA|Cork]]\n|21-404\n|467\n|57 games\n|2008\u2013present\n|8.2\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=center|4\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Eddie Keher]]\n|[[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]]\n|35-336\n|441\n|50 games\n|1959-1977\n|8.8\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=center|5\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Eoin Kelly (Tipperary hurler)|Eoin Kelly]]\n|[[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]]\n|21-369\n|432\n|63 games\n|2000-2014\n|6.8